<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Bayes' Theorem</h1>=20


<p><b>Bayes can do magic!</b></p>=20
<p>Ever wondered how computers learn about people?</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/sh=
oe-laces.jpg" alt=3D"shoe laces" height=3D"151" width=3D"229"></p>=20

	<h3>Example:</h3>=20

	<p>An internet search for "movie automatic shoe laces" brings up "Back to =
the future"</p>=20
	<p>Has the search engine watched the movie? No, but it knows from lots of =
other searches what people are <b>probably</b> looking for.</p>=20
	<p>And it calculates that probability using Bayes' Theorem.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p><span class=3D"large">Bayes' Theorem</span> is a way of finding a <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/probability.html">probability</a> when=
 we know certain other probabilities.</p>=20
<p>The formula is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(A|B) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>P(A=
) P(B|A)</em><strong>P(B)</strong></span></p><br>
<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;">Which tells us:</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>how often A happens <i>given that B happens</i>, written <b>P(A|B)</=
b>,</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;">When we know:</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>how often B happens <i>given that A happens</i>, written <b>P(B|A)</=
b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>and how likely A is on its own, written <b>P(A)</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>and how likely B is on its own, written <b>P(B)</b></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>Let us say P(Fire) means how often there is fire, and P(Smoke) means how=
 often we see smoke, then:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center">P(Fire|Smoke) means how often there is fire when we can=
 see smoke<br>
P(Smoke|Fire) means how often we can see smoke when there is fire</p>=20
<p>So the formula kind of tells us "forwards" <span class=3D"center">P(Fire=
|Smoke)</span> when we know "backwards" <span class=3D"center">P(Smoke|Fire=
)</span></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/=
smoke.jpg" alt=3D"smoke" height=3D"230" width=3D"125"><br>
<i>Home Bonfire</i></div>
<div class=3D"h3">Example:=20
<ul>=20
	<li>dangerous fires are rare (1%)</li>=20
	<li>but smoke is fairly common (10%) due to barbecues,</li>=20
	<li>and 90% of dangerous fires make smoke</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>
<p>We can then discover the <b>probability of dangerous Fire when there is =
Smoke</b>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">P(Fire|Smoke) <em>=3D</em></span><sp=
an class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>P(Fire) P(Smoke|Fire)</em><strong=
>P(Smoke)</strong></span></span>
<span class=3D"lt">=3D</span><span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>1=
% x 90%</em><strong>10%</strong></span></span>
<span class=3D"lt">=3D</span><span class=3D"rt">9%</span>
</div>
<p>So it is still worth checking out any smoke to be sure.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/pi=
cnic.jpg" alt=3D"picnic" height=3D"131" width=3D"240"></p>=20

	<h3>Example: Picnic Day</h3>=20

	<p>You are planning a picnic today, but the morning is cloudy</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>Oh no! 50% of all rainy days start off cloudy!</li>=20
		<li>But cloudy mornings are common (about 40% of days start cloudy)</li>=
=20
		<li>And this is usually a dry month (only 3 of 30 days tend to be rainy, =
or 10%)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p><b>What is the chance of rain during the day?</b></p>=20
	<p>We will use Rain to mean rain during the day, and Cloud to mean cloudy =
morning.</p>=20
	<p>The chance of Rain given Cloud is written P(Rain|Cloud)</p>=20
	<p>So let's put that in the formula:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">P(Rain|Cloud) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"=
><em>P(Rain) P(Cloud|Rain)</em><strong>P(Cloud)</strong></span></p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>P(Rain) is Probability of Rain <em>=3D</em> 10%</li>=20
		<li>P(Cloud|Rain) is Probability of Cloud, given that Rain happens <em>=
=3D</em> 50%</li>=20
		<li>P(Cloud) is Probability of Cloud <em>=3D</em> 40%</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">P(Rain|Cloud) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"=
><em>0,1 x 0,5</em><strong>0,4</strong></span>  <em>=3D</em> .125</p>=20
	<p>Or a 12,5% chance of rain. Not too bad, let's have a picnic!</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Just 4 Numbers</h2>=20

<p>Imagine 100 people at a party, and you tally how many wear pink or not, =
and if a man or not, and get these numbers:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/baye=
s-table-pink-man.svg" alt=3D"bayes table" height=3D"143" width=3D"284"></p>=
=20
<p>Bayes' Theorem is based off just those 4 numbers!</p>=20
<p>Let us do some totals:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/baye=
s-table-pink-man-tot.svg" alt=3D"bayes table totals" height=3D"143" width=
=3D"284"></p>=20
<p>And calculate some probabilities:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>the probability of being a man is P(Man) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"i=
ntbl"><em>40</em><strong>100</strong></span> <em>=3D</em> 0,4</li>=20
	<li>the probability of wearing pink is P(Pink) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D=
"intbl"><em>25</em><strong>100</strong></span> <em>=3D</em> 0,25</li>=20
	<li>the probability that a man wears pink is P(Pink|Man) <em>=3D</em> <spa=
n class=3D"intbl"><em>5</em><strong>40</strong></span> <em>=3D</em> 0,125</=
li>=20
	<li>the probability that a person wearing pink is a man <b>P(Man|Pink) <em=
>=3D</em> ...</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/arr=
ow-pup-rip.jpg" alt=3D"puppy rips" height=3D"101" width=3D"120"></p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>And then the puppy arrives! Such a cute puppy.</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>But all your data is<b> ripped up</b>! Only 3 values survive:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b> P(Man) <em>=3D</em> 0,4,</b></li>=20
	<li><b>P(Pink) <em>=3D</em> 0,25 and</b></li>=20
	<li><b>P(Pink|Man) <em>=3D</em> 0,125</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p class=3D"center">Can you discover <b>P(Man|Pink)</b> ?</p>=20
<p>Imagine a pink-wearing guest leaves money behind ... was it a man? We ca=
n answer this question using Bayes' Theorem:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Man|Pink) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><e=
m>P(Man) P(Pink|Man)</em><strong>P(Pink)</strong></span></p>=20
<!-- P(Man|Pink)<em>=3D</em> P(Man)P(Pink|Man)/P(Pink) -->=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Man|Pink) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><e=
m>0,4 =C3=97 0,125</em><strong>0,25</strong></span> <em>=3D</em> 0,2</p>=20
<!-- P(Man|Pink)<em>=3D</em> 0.4*0.125/0.25 <em>=3D</em> 0.2 --> <i>Note: i=
f we still had the raw data we could calculate directly <span class=3D"intb=
l"><em>5</em><strong>25</strong></span> <em>=3D</em> 0,2</i>=20


<h2>Being General</h2>=20

<p>Why does it work?</p>=20
<p>Let us replace the numbers with letters:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/baye=
s-table.svg" alt=3D"bayes table" height=3D"143" width=3D"308"></p>=20
<p>Now let us look at <b>probabilities</b>. So we take some ratios:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>the overall probability of "A" is P(A) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"int=
bl"><em>s+t</em><strong>s+t+u+v</strong></span></li>=20
	<li>the probability of "B given A" is P(B|A) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"i=
ntbl"><em>s</em><strong>s+t</strong></span></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And then multiply them together like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/baye=
s-table-math-a.svg" alt=3D"bayes table math P(A)" height=3D"204" width=3D"6=
30"></p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>Now let us do that again but use <b>P(B)</b> and <b>P(A|B)</b>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/baye=
s-table-math-b.svg" alt=3D"bayes table math P(B)" height=3D"201" width=3D"6=
42"></p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>Both ways get the <b>same result</b> of <span class=3D"intbl"><em>s</em>=
<strong>s+t+u+v</strong></span></p>=20
<p>So we can see that:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(B) P(A|B) <em>=3D</em> P(A) P(B|A)</p>=20
<p><i>Nice and symmetrical isn't it?</i></p>=20
<p>It actually <i>has</i> to be symmetrical as we can swap rows and columns=
 and get the same top-left corner.</p>=20
<p>And it is also <b>Bayes Formula</b> ... just divide both sides by P(B):<=
/p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(A|B) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>P(A=
) P(B|A)</em><strong>P(B)</strong></span></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Remembering</h2>=20

<p>First think "AB AB AB" then remember to group it like: "AB <em>=3D</em> =
A BA / B"</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(<span class=3D"largest">A</span>|<span class=3D=
"largest">B</span>) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>P(<span class=3D=
"largest">A</span>) P(<span class=3D"largest">B</span>|<span class=3D"large=
st">A</span>)</em><strong>P(<span class=3D"largest">B</span>)</strong></spa=
n></p>=20


<h2>Cat Allergy?</h2>=20

<p>One of the famous uses for Bayes Theorem is <a href=3D"https://www.maths=
isfun.com/data/probability-false-negatives-positives.html">False Positives =
and False Negatives</a>.</p>=20
<p>For those we have two possible cases for "A", such as <b>Pass</b>/<b>Fai=
l</b> (or Yes/No and so on)</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Allergy or Not?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ca=
t.jpg" alt=3D"cat" height=3D"151" width=3D"100"></p>=20
	<p>Hunter says she is itchy. There is a test for Allergy to Cats, but this=
 test is not always right:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>For people that <b>really do</b> have the allergy, the test says "Yes=
" <b>80%</b> of the time</li>=20
		<li>For people that <b>do not</b> have the allergy, the test says "Yes" <=
b>10%</b> of the time ("false positive")</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p><span class=3D"large"> If 1% of the population have the allergy, and <b=
>Hunter's test says "Yes"</b>, what are the chances that Hunter really has =
the allergy?</span></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>We want to know the chance of having the allergy when test says "Yes", w=
ritten <b>P(Allergy|Yes)</b></p>=20
<p>Let's get our formula:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Allergy|Yes) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"=
><em>P(Allergy) P(Yes|Allergy)</em><strong>P(Yes)</strong></span></p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>P(Allergy) is Probability of Allergy <em>=3D</em> 1%</li>=20
	<li>P(Yes|Allergy) is Probability of test saying "Yes" for people with all=
ergy <em>=3D</em> 80%</li>=20
	<li>P(Yes) is Probability of test saying "Yes" (to anyone) <em>=3D</em> ??=
%</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Oh no! We <b>don't know</b> what the <b>general</b> chance of the test s=
aying "Yes" is ...</p>=20
<p>... but we can calculate it by adding up those <b>with</b>, and those <b=
>without</b> the allergy:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>1% have the allergy, and the test says "Yes" to 80% of them</li>=20
	<li>99% do <b>not</b> have the allergy&nbsp;and the test says "Yes" to 10%=
 of them</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Let's add that up:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Yes) <em>=3D</em> 1% =C3=97 80% + 99% =C3=97 10=
% <em>=3D</em> 10,7%</p>=20
<p>Which means that about 10,7% of the population will get a "Yes" result.<=
/p>=20
<p>So now we can complete our formula:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Allergy|Yes) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"=
><em>1% =C3=97 80%</em><strong>10,7%</strong></span>  <em>=3D</em> 7,48%</p=
>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Allergy|Yes) <em>=3D</em> about <b>7%</b></p>=
=20
<p>This is the same result we got on <span class=3D"center"><a href=3D"http=
s://www.mathsisfun.com/data/probability-false-negatives-positives.html">Fal=
se Positives and False Negatives</a></span>.</p>=20
<p>In fact we can write a special version of the Bayes' formula just for th=
ings like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(A|B) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>P(A=
)P(B|A)</em><strong> P(A)P(B|A) + P(not A)P(B|not A)</strong></span></p>=20


<h2>"A" With Three (or more) Cases</h2>=20

<p>We just saw "A" with two cases (A and not A), which we took care of in t=
he bottom line.</p>=20
<p>When "A" has 3 or more cases we include them all in the bottom line:</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(A1|B) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>P(=
A1)P(B|A1)</em><strong> P(A1)P(B|A1) + P(A2)P(B|A2) + P(A3)P(B|A3) + ...and=
 so on</strong></span></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ar=
t-show.jpg" alt=3D"art show" height=3D"137" width=3D"240"></p>=20

	<h3>Example: The Art Competition has entries from three painters: Pam, Pia=
 and Pablo</h3>=20

	<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>

<ul>=20
	<li>Pam put in 15 paintings, 4% of her works have won First Prize</li>=20
	<li>Pia put in 5 paintings, 6% of her works have won First Prize</li>=20
	<li>Pablo put in 10 paintings, 3% of his works have won First Prize</li>=
=20
</ul>=20
<p>What is the chance that Pam will win First Prize?</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">P(Pam|First) <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><=
em>P(Pam)P(First|Pam)</em><strong> P(Pam)P(First|Pam) + P(Pia)P(First|Pia) =
+ P(Pablo)P(First|Pablo)</strong></span></p>=20
<p>Put in the values:</p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">P(Pam|First) <em>=3D</em></span><spa=
n class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>(15/30) =C3=97 4%</em><strong> (15=
/30) =C3=97 4% + (5/30) =C3=97 6% + (10/30) =C3=97 3%</strong></span></span=
>
</div>
<p>Multiply all by 30 (makes calculation easier):</p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">P(Pam|First) <em>=3D</em></span><spa=
n class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>15 =C3=97 4%</em><strong> 15 =C3=
=97 4% + 5 =C3=97 6% + 10 =C3=97 3%</strong></span></span>
<span class=3D"lt">=3D</span><span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>0=
,6</em><strong>0,6 + 0,3 + 0,3</strong></span></span>
<span class=3D"lt">=3D</span><span class=3D"rt">50%</span>
</div>
<p>A good chance!</p>=20
<p>Pam isn't the most successful artist, but she did put in lots of entries=
.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"fun">=20

<h3>Now, back to Search Engines.</h3>=20

<p>Search Engines take this idea and scale it up a lot (plus some other tri=
cks).</p>=20
<p>It makes them look like they can read your mind!</p>=20
<p>It can also be used for mail filters, music recommendation services and =
more.</p>=20
</div>

